      • addToMap

        public static <K> void addToMap​(Map<K,​Number> m,
                                K k,
                                Number i)
        Adds to a mapped number. If m does not already contain the key k then i is mapped to k. Otherwise the value for k is obtained from m and i is added to it using Generic_Math.add(java.lang.Number, java.lang.Number). This may result in infinite values being added to m or ArithmeticExceptions being thrown all depending on the result of any additions as calculated via Generic_Math.add(java.lang.Number, java.lang.Number).
        Type Parameters:
        K - Key
        Parameters:
        m - The map that is to be added to.
        k - The key which value is added to or initialised.
        i - The amount to be added to the map.

      • addToMap

        public static <K,​V1 extends Number,​V2 extends Number> void addToMap​(Map<K,​V1> u,
                                                                                Map<K,​V2> uf)
        This will add the values in uf to the values in u for any existing keys. Where keys in u do not exist, the the numerical value of these in uf are put in u. This may result in infinite numbers being values in u (where the resulting addition is beyond the bounds of the type of V1). Existing keys in u that are mapped to null values are removed. NaN values may also be added to u if infinite values added are the opposite infinities. ArithmeticExceptions might also be throws if NaN type values are attempted to be added to types that cannot represent NaN.
        Type Parameters:
        K - The types of key in u and f.
        V1 - The type of Number values in u.
        V2 - The type of Number values in uf.
        Parameters:
        u - The map to updated by adding to the values from uf.
        uf - The map to update u from by adding values.

        public static long[] getCounts​(HashSet s0,
